Impromptu market and bread shopping @dupainetdesidees - picked up beautiful fresh strawberries, asparagus and tomatoes as well as terrine, rabbit (!) and more! (And if you have Alexa enabled, apologies if my IG Live turned it on. I’ve been resisting using it but thought I’d finally give it a try when I bought a new speaker that included it…and she decided to start playing music during the video, and some commenters said me talking about it turned their “Alexas” on too😅😁) What do you look forward to most at the market in the summer?

node.text:
The tourteau fromager is a curiosity from the Charentes. People have often pointed out that things look “burnt” to them in photos, who may not be used to darkly cooked breads, etc., but these are meant to be completely black on top. But inside is a light, spongy cheesecake that doesn’t taste burnt at all. (Swipe left👈on the pic to see inside.) I’ve tried to get that same black topping when I’ve baked them at home and I suspect a wood 🔥fire helps, which I don’t have (and the special molds, which I bought), but they are something that’s easy to buy (in France), which is what most people do…
.
#cheesecake #tourteaufromager #charentais
.
There’s a recipe in my book MY PARIS KITCHEN to make a version but getting them to look like the store-bought ones, as shown, is tricky

Excited that Drinking French: The Iconic Cocktails, Apéritifs, and Café Traditions of France, with 160 Recipes is a finalist for a “Best New Cocktail or Bartending Book” for @tales_of_the_cocktail Spirited Awards for 2021. It’s nice to be recognized and thanks for everyone out there who supported (and even better, used!) Drinking French. Also a big shout out to some of the other great books nominated by friends and colleagues including @chloefrechette @juliabainbridge and @brianbartels in the same category, and pals (and Apéro Hour fan favorites @btparsons @robertosimonson @ivymix as well as David Wondrich who’s not on IG but is a spirited drinking companion, on occasion…
.
And thanks to @edandcamera and @georgedolesefoodstylist for the fun photo sessions and *everyone* at @tenspeedpress and @tenspeedpress for working so well on the book with me - à santé! 🥂🍾 & especially to everyone of you who got a copy of DRINKING FRENCH 🥰🥰 and joined along in the fun (and sometimes, emotions) during all the IG Live Apéro Hours too, during an especially challenging year #drinkingfrench 🇫🇷

node.text: I used to find meat in jelly a little odd (and I had an editor nix a fruit jelly recipe I was planning to put in a book, too, so not everyone is ready for jelly…) but I’ve come to love this ‘sort of’ jambon persillé. (Note: Editors don’t like single quotation marks either…🤷🏼😅) But this isn’t a true “persillé” since there’s no - or very, very little - parsley and it’s ham along with some other kind of cooked pork. My local friends picked it up at the market in Toucy, Burgundy, and it was the best one I’ve ever had.
